<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Ed Brubaker on jverkamp.com</title><link>https://blog.jverkamp.com/reviews/writers/ed-brubaker/</link><description>Recent content in Ed Brubaker on jverkamp.com</description><generator>Hugo -- gohugo.io</generator><language>en-us</language><atom:link href="https://blog.jverkamp.com/reviews/writers/ed-brubaker/atom.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Captain America: The Winter Soldier</title><link>https://blog.jverkamp.com/2021/05/27/captain-america-the-winter-soldier/</link><pubDate>Thu, 27 May 2021 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://blog.jverkamp.com/2021/05/27/captain-america-the-winter-soldier/</guid><description>&lt;p>From &lt;a href="https://blog.jverkamp.com/2021/05/12/thor-the-dark-world/">one of the weakest&lt;/a> MCU movies to one of the strongest. I loved the first solo entry of Captain American and the second is even better. Much like &lt;a href="https://blog.jverkamp.com/2021/05/27/captain-america-the-winter-soldier/">last time&lt;/a>, I very much enjoyed this movie.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>It&amp;rsquo;s a solid contrast against the first Captain America (blind optimistic patriotism versus a darker world, where even your friends&amp;hellip; might not be). It&amp;rsquo;s made all the better having already seen the future of Sam and Bucky/The Winter Soldier now. Last time through, I was hoping they could pull off all the new characters and now&amp;hellip; I think they did.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>This time around (and so far), the top of my list for the year. An excellent movie.&lt;/p>
